					<msContents>
						<summary>

						<p>On a rock below the hill to the north of the village.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājakēsarivarman (Āditya I) Year 24: 895 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This inscription is found clumsily engraved in bold characters. The stone had not been dressed properly before engraving, hence letters are not clearly visible in several places. The portion concerned of the rock was ruled before engraving the inscription.</p>						

						<p>It records that Ariñjigai Vembaṉ of Paralūr in Uḍaikāṭṭu-nāḍu had caused a tank (Puttēri) dug and endowed a quarter <hi rend="italic">śey</hi> of land for providing a sluice <hi rend="italic">(tūmbu)</hi> to that tank and stipulated that a <hi rend="italic">kuṛuṇi</hi> of paddy per <hi rend="italic">mā</hi> could be levied for its maintenance. </p>						

						</summary>
